==English==

===Etymology===
From {{S.}} ''[[embargar]]'' 'to arrest' and {{E.}} ''[[barge]]'' 'to force'.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP|US}} {{IPA|/əmˈbɑrdʒ/}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɑː(r)dʒ|-ɑː(r)dʒ]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|embarg|es}}

# {{rfv-sense}} {{transitive}} To impose oneself upon another, often against their will.
# {{rfv-sense}} {{transitive}} To forcefully share an unwanted opinion.
#*In his love for her, he had unintentionally '''embarged''' himself upon her, and only wanted her to return the love he so dearly felt for her.
# {{transitive}} To [[embargo]].
#*'''1979''', Westel Woodbury Willoughby, ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=7J2ua2xblxcC&pg=PA174&dq=embarge&ei=ekJcR-23II3GiQH-nviHBA&sig=tk4ooNpsLxGDMAKyY7MqEWI8Crw Japan's Case Examined]'', page 174
#*: This '''embarge''' is termed a moral one because it imposes no legal restraints upon would-be exporters, for there are no statutes providing for this. 
# {{intransitive}} To board a [[barge]]; to [[embark]].
#*'''1843''', Frederick William Fairholt, ''Lord Mayors' Pageants'', page 152
#*: [...] where the Lord Mayor, aldermen, and their attendants take barge; also the Grocers Company do likewise '''embarge''', [...].


